example for usage of static

class Parent {
    // static method
    static void display(){
    System.out.println("Parent display");
    }
}


class Child extends Parent{
    // looks overriding the display method but its not.
    static void display(){
    System.out.println("Child display");
    }
}


Parent obj = new Child()

obj.display() // Output: "Parent display"
              // Static method is called from parent class, not in the actual object of child class.

      Why this happens?
      this happens because Static methods are resolved at compile time
      Instance methods are resolved at runtime

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

// instance methods can access both instance variable and static members
class Example {

    String instanceVar = "instance";

    static String staticVar = "static"

    public void instanceMethod(){
    // Can access instance variable;
        System.void.println(instanceVar);

    anotherInstanceMethod();

    System.out.print(staticVar);

    // can access static method
    staticMethod();
    }

    public void anotherInstanceMethod(){
        System.out.println("another instance method");
    }

    static void staticMethod(){
        System.out.println("static method");
    }
}



for static methods it can only access with the same static members directly

class Example {

    String instanceVar = "instance";

    static String staticVar = "static"

    static void staticMethod1(){
    // Cannot access instance variable;
        System.void.println(instanceVar);

    // same with this
    anotherInstanceMethod();

    // can can acess static variable
    System.out.print(staticVar);

    // can access static method
    staticMethod();
    }

    public void anotherInstanceMethod(){
        System.out.println("another instance method");
    }

    static void staticMethod(){
        System.out.println("static method");
    }
}

// static variable can access instance variable via object refence

class Example {
    String instance = "instance"


    static void staticMethod(){
    System.out.print(instance) // cannot access directly

    // can access through object reference
    Example obj = new Example()
    System.out.println(obj.instance));
    obj.instanceMethod();
    }

    public void instanceMethod() {
    System.out.println("instance method called");
    }

}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

static in code blocks

sometimes we initialize static variables directly during declaration, However, if the static variables require
multi-statement logic during initialization we can use the static code block instead.

for instance, let's initialize a list of objects with some predefined values using static block of code.

public class StaticBlock {
    public static List<String> ranks = new LinkList<>();

    //static code block

    static {
       ranks.add("Lieutenant");
       ranks.add("Captain");
       ranks.add("Major");
    }

    static {
      ranks.add("Colonel");
      ranks.add("General");
    }
}

// static inner class

   so java allow us to create nested class

   so in general there's two nested class architecture

   1. nested classes that we declare static are called static nested classes
   2. nested classes that are non-static are called inner classes

   also take note that these two behave different the inner class have access to all members
   within the enclosing class including the private ones, whereas the static nested classes only have
   access to static members of the outer class.

example codes

// for static nested class
class OuterClass{
    private static String staticMessage = "static message";
    private String instanceMessage = "Instance message";

   static class staticNestedClass{
    void display(){
        // can access static members outside of class
        System.out.println(staticMessage);

        // cannot access instance members
        System.out.println(instanceMessage);

        // can create its own instance member
        String ex = "hello";
        System.out.println(ex);
    }
   }
}

// for inner class example

class OuterClass {
    private static String staticMessage = "Static message";
    private String instanceMessage = "Instance message";

    // Inner class (non-static)
    class InnerClass {
        void display() {
            // can access BOTH static members
            System.out.println(staticMessage);    // Works

            // can access instance members too!
            System.out.println(instanceMessage);  // Works

            // can even access private instance members
            String combined = staticMessage + " - " + instanceMessage;
            System.out.println(combined);
        }
    }
}






































































